    <!-- Content Row -->
    <div class="bs-example">
     <h3>
      <strong>
       FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTION's
      </strong>
     </h3>
     <div id="accordion" class="panel-group">
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseOne" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          What are the benefits of an extended beachfront Oceanway path?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseOne">
        <div class="panel-body">
         The Tugun to Bilinga (T2B) Oceanway will connect the existing Oceanway paths that end at Bilinga SLSC and O'Connor Park, near the Tugun SLSC. This 1.7km section would lead to approximately 8km of continuous beachfront Oceanway stretching from Flat Rock Creek, Currumbin to Snapper Rocks in Coolangatta. The extension of a beachfront Oceanway - allowing access to this amenity for all members of the public including those with disabilities, the infirm, and the very young and elderly - will have numerous social and economic benefits for the Southern Gold Coast.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseTwo" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          What materials will the T2B Oceanway path be made of?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseTwo">
        <div class="panel-body">
         In the Tugun to Bilinga Oceanway
         <a target="new" href="Images/report/t2b-planning-report.pdf">
          Planning Report
         </a>
         dated October 2011, council recommended a concrete path. However council may consider alternative materials. Whatever materials are chosen, the primary consideration is that the path is compliant with the Disability Discrimination Act.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseThree" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          Where exactly will the path go?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseThree">
        <div class="panel-body">
         Council's 2011 Planning Report clearly marked out an alignment (route) for the path which is predominantly on public land on the Pacific Parade road reserve, on the landward side of the dune system and seawall (also called the
         <a target="new" href="Images/report/a-line-seawall.pdf">
          A-Line wall
         </a>
         ).  Most of the road reserve has been "developed" to some extent, as over the years there has been encroachment on this public land by way of lawns, gardens, showers, concrete paths, fencing, etc.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseFour" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          What effects will the path have on the dune system?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseFour">
        <div class="panel-body">
         Council's proposed path alignment is predominantly on the Pacific Parade road reserve which is on the inland, western side of the dunes and seawall. For some of the more narrower sections, alternate walkway structures may be required, for example wooden walkways, which have been installed at multiple locations around the Australian coastline, and would be a far better alternative to the tracks that currently are gouged out of the mid-dune system (eg. John Street) in order to get around these "pinch points".
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseFive" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          Isn't work already being done to protect the dune system there?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseFive">
        <div class="panel-body">
         With acknowledgement of the efforts made by a dune care group in one small patch of the dunes at the bottom of Sea Street and council's weed management efforts, there is clear evidence that much of the dune system has been left to degrade over the years.  A recent assessment showed that almost all of the dune system was overgrown by multiple varieties of invasive weed species and introduced plants.  Additionally, in some areas residents have  encroached into the dune system with lawn area. Council’s own Planning Scheme  Policy 15, which outlines the management regime for Coastal Dune Areas, states  that mown turf does not have the ability to trap windblown sand travelling  above the ground level, and this regime is not sustainable, and is not  considered acceptable long term. “To allow the land to be maintained as private  property, without an approved or monitored management regime will reduce the  natural heritage values of the ocean front land and would be detrimental to the  sustainability of other dunal environment”
         <a target="_parent" href="Images/report/dune_plants_12_policy_15.pdf">
          (Policy 15 – Management of Coastal  Dune Areas)
         </a>
         . Additionally, numerous beach access tracks have been made by  residents increasing the possibility of erosion, and the dunes are a dumping  ground for garden clippings and prunings, general rubbish such as plastics and  bottles, various items of disused infrastructure such as stair rails, and large  pieces of household equipment (eg. a canoe). We believe the most effective way  to improve the health of the dune system along this stretch of coast is to open  up access to allow protection, ownership and stewardship of the dunes that run  along it with support from community groups.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseSix" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          Will the path damage native trees and wildlife?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseSix">
        <div class="panel-body">
         It is true that council's preferred path alignment would require the cutting back or removal of some native trees, but all efforts would be made to keep this to a minimum.  Wherever possible these trees, mainly pandanus, may be transplanted.  Replacement trees can be planted and grown back, but everyone would of course prefer that tree removal is kept to a minimum.  As the path alignment is predominantly on the developed road reserve there can be zero to minimal impact expected to native fauna.  It should be noted there was no mention of fauna/native animal species in the council's Tugun to Bilinga Planning Report.  Overall there may be a very small impact on the environment during the construction of the T2B Oceanway in return for a far greater, longer term environmental gain (together with a significant increase in social, health and economic values).
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseSeven" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          Didn't a survey show the majority of the community wanted this section of the Oceanway put on Golden Four Drive?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseSeven">
        <div class="panel-body">
         A survey was conducted on behalf of council and a
         <a href="Images/report/tugun-bilinga-consultation-report.pdf">
          Consultation Report
         </a>
         released in May 2012.  However the report itself said:
         <br />
         <br />
         <blockquote>
          <em>
           <strong>
            "The consultation process did not focus on a random sample of respondents.  Instead, the feedback process enabled community members who reside, or own property, in proximity to the proposed Oceanway and accessway improvements an opportunity to provide extensive feedback to the proposals.
           </strong>
          </em>
          "
         </blockquote>
         This alone calls into question the validity of the survey and its findings.  Expert independent analysis of this survey also seriously questions its outcomes, finding the survey:
         <br />
         <br />
         <blockquote>
          <em>
           <strong>
            "DID NOT COMPLY with the normal standards of statistical riqour, independence and transparency necessary to justify rejection of the Oceanway proposal",  and that "the method was neither random nor representative but biased in favour of a small stakeholder group of Golden Four Drive beachfront residents who overwhelmingly oppose the proposal".
           </strong>
          </em>
         </blockquote>
         <br />
         In short, the survey results are not to be trusted.
         <br />
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseEight" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          What's wrong with putting the Oceanway on Golden Four Drive?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseEight">
        <div class="panel-body">
         As it is now, Golden Four Drive is an unsuitable route for  pedestrians, let alone people on bikes, in wheelchairs or in prams, or the  elderly. It is well-used by cars, there are numerous driveway and street  crossings coming out onto the road, and the footpath is narrow, bumpy and full  of obstacles such as overhanging tree branches and bus shelters. Council’s own  advice says that, “The alternate current facilities along Golden Four Drive are  substandard and are not conducive to encouraging people to walk and cycle for  more trips and encourage healthier and more sustainable transport choices from  coastal residents and visitors” (
         <a href="Images/report/council_20131212.pdf">
          Adopted Report, December 2013
         </a>
         ). Main  Roads and Transport has started a project to upgrade Golden Four Drive in  sections over a number of years, and there is provision for a cycleway and  access path in these plans. However not all cyclists are comfortable riding on  the roadside, and it still is likely to leave pedestrians and other users  having to cross roads and/or possible driveway points. Then there are the  amenity and health aspects of using a path which runs along a busy road compared  with a dedicated and safe beachside path. Additionally, there are technical  issues involved with upgrading Golden Four Drive such as moving infrastructure  and reduced car parking space.
         <br />
         <img alt="Golden Four Drive, showing parked cars, traffic, and path ways that are uneven with signage from shops and polls. " src="Images/carousel/g4d1.jpg" />
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <!-- /.panel -->
      <div class="panel panel-default">
       <div class="panel-heading">
        <h4 class="panel-title">
         <a href="#collapseNine" data-parent="#accordion" data-toggle="collapse" class="accordion-toggle">
          Does the path meet coastal planning and other policies and regulations?
         </a>
        </h4>
       </div>
       <div class="panel-collapse collapse" id="collapseNine">
        <div class="panel-body">
         While T2B Oceanway does pose challenges in terms of policies and regulations, these were investigated by the council’s  Infrastructure Development Group using the resources of Legal Services, City  Governance. No major legal impediments were noted in council’s Tugun to Bilinga  Oceanway Planning Report. In fact council has reported that the only reason the  Oceanway link between  Tugun-Bilinga was put on hold was “a result of the current economic conditions”
         <a target="new" href="Images/report/council_20131212.pdf">
          (Adopted Report, December 2013)
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /.panel -->
     </div>
     <!-- /.panel-group -->
    </div>
    <!-- /.col-lg-12 -->
   </div>
